aa(lp22
VWe know depression through metaphors.
p23
aVEmily Dickinson was able to convey it in language,
p24
aVGoya in an image.
p25
aVHalf the purpose of art is to describe such iconic states.
p26
aa(lp27
VAs for me, I had always thought myself tough,
p28
aVone of the people who could survive
p29
aVif I'd been sent to a concentration camp.
p30
aa(lp31
VIn 1991, I had a series of losses.
p32
aVMy mother died,
p33
aVa relationship I'd been in ended,
p34
aVI moved back to the United States from some years abroad,
p35
aVand I got through all of those experiences intact.
p36
aa(lp37
VBut in 1994, three years later,
p38
aVI found myself losing interest in almost everything.
p39
aVI didn't want to do any of the things I had previously wanted to do,
p40
aVand I didn't know why.
p41
aVThe opposite of depression is not happiness, but vitality.
p42
aVAnd it was vitality
p43
aVthat seemed to seep away from me in that moment.
p44
aVEverything there was to do seemed like too much work.
p45
aVI would come home
p46
aVand I would see the red light flashing on my answering machine,
p47
aVand instead of being thrilled to hear from my friends,
p48
aVI would think,
p49
aV"What a lot of people that is to have to call back."
p50
aVOr I would decide I should have lunch,
p51
aVand then I would think, but I'd have to get the food out
p52
aVand put it on a plate
p53
aVand cut it up and chew it and swallow it,
p54
aVand it felt to me like the Stations of the Cross.
p55
aa(lp56
VAnd one of the things that often gets lost in discussions of depression
p57
aVis that you know it's ridiculous.
p58
aVYou know it's ridiculous while you're experiencing it.
p59
aVYou know that most people manage
p60
aVto listen to their messages and eat lunch
p61
aVand organize themselves to take a shower
p62
aVand go out the front door
p63
aVand that it's not a big deal,
p64
aVand yet you are nonetheless in its grip
p65
aVand you are unable to figure out any way around it.
p66
aVAnd so I began to feel myself doing less
p67
aVand thinking less
p68
aVand feeling less.
p69
aVIt was a kind of nullity.
p70
aa(lp71
VAnd then the anxiety set in.
p72
aVIf you told me that I'd have to be depressed for the next month,
p73
aVI would say, "As long I know it'll be over in November, I can do it."
p74
aVBut if you said to me,
p75
aV"You have to have acute anxiety for the next month,"
p76
aVI would rather slit my wrist than go through it.
p77
aVIt was the feeling all the time
p78
aVlike that feeling you have if you're walking
p79
aVand you slip or trip and the ground is rushing up at you,
p80
aVbut instead of lasting half a second, the way that does,
p81
aVit lasted for six months.
p82
aVIt's a sensation of being afraid all the time
p83
aVbut not even knowing what it is that you're afraid of.
p84
aVAnd it was at that point that I began to think
p85
aVthat it was just too painful to be alive,
p86
aVand that the only reason not to kill oneself
p87
aVwas so as not to hurt other people.
p88
aa(lp89
VAnd finally one day, I woke up
p90
aVand I thought perhaps I'd had a stroke,
p91
aVbecause I lay in bed completely frozen,
p92
aVlooking at the telephone, thinking,
p93
aV"Something is wrong and I should call for help,"
p94
aVand I couldn't reach out my arm
p95
aVand pick up the phone and dial.
p96
aVAnd finally, after four full hours of my lying and staring at it,
p97
aVthe phone rang,
p98
aVand somehow I managed to pick it up,
p99
aVand it was my father, and I said,
p100
aV"I'm in serious trouble. We need to do something."
p101
aa(lp102
VThe next day I started with the medications and the therapy.
p103
aVAnd I also started reckoning with this terrible question:
p104
aVIf I'm not the tough person
p105
aVwho could have made it through a concentration camp,
p106
aVthen who am I?
p107
aVAnd if I have to take medication,
p108
aVis that medication making me more fully myself,
p109
aVor is it making me someone else?
p110
aVAnd how do I feel about it if it's making me someone else?
