aa(lp147
VDepression is the flaw in love.
p148
aVIf you were married to someone and thought,
p149
aV"Well, if my wife dies, I'll find another one,"
p150
aVit wouldn't be love as we know it.
p151
aVThere's no such thing as love without the anticipation of loss,
p152
aVand that specter of despair can be the engine of intimacy.
p153
aa(lp154
VThere are three things people tend to confuse:
p155
aVdepression, grief and sadness.
p156
aVGrief is explicitly reactive.
p157
aVIf you have a loss and you feel incredibly unhappy,
p158
aVand then, six months later,
p159
aVyou are still deeply sad, but you're functioning a little better,
p160
aVit's probably grief,
p161
aVand it will probably ultimately resolve itself in some measure.
p162
aVIf you experience a catastrophic loss,
p163
aVand you feel terrible,
p164
aVand six months later you can barely function at all,
p165
aVthen it's probably a depression that was triggered
p166
aVby the catastrophic circumstances.
p167
aVThe trajectory tells us a great deal.
p168
aVPeople think of depression as being just sadness.
p169
aVIt's much, much too much sadness,
p170
aVmuch too much grief
p171
aVat far too slight a cause.
