aa(lp173
VAs I set out to understand depression,
p174
aVand to interview people who had experienced it,
p175
aVI found that there were people who seemed, on the surface,
p176
aVto have what sounded like relatively mild depression
p177
aVwho were nonetheless utterly disabled by it.
p178
aVAnd there were other people who had what sounded
p179
aVas they described it like terribly severe depression
p180
aVwho nonetheless had good lives
p181
aVin the interstices between their depressive episodes.
p182
aVAnd I set out to find out what it is that causes some people
p183
aVto be more resilient than other people.
p184
aVWhat are the mechanisms that allow people to survive?
p185
aVAnd I went out and I interviewed person after person
p186
aVwho was suffering with depression.
p187
aa(lp188
VOne of the first people I interviewed
p189
aVdescribed depression as a slower way of being dead,
p190
aVand that was a good thing for me to hear early on
p191
aVbecause it reminded me that that slow way of being dead
p192
aVcan lead to actual deadness,
p193
aVthat this is a serious business.
p194
aVIt's the leading disability worldwide,
p195
aVand people die of it every day.
