aa(lp197
VOne of the people I talked to when I was trying to understand this
p198
aVwas a beloved friend who I had known for many years,
p199
aVand who had had a psychotic episode in her freshman year of college,
p200
aVand then plummeted into a horrific depression.
p201
aVShe had bipolar illness,
p202
aVor manic depression, as it was then known.
p203
aVAnd then she did very well for many years on lithium,
p204
aVand then eventually, she was taken off her lithium
p205
aVto see how she would do without it,
p206
aVand she had another psychosis,
p207
aVand then plunged into the worst depression that I had ever seen
p208
aVin which she sat in her parents' apartment,
p209
aVmore or less catatonic, essentially without moving,
p210
aVday after day after day.
p211
aVAnd when I interviewed her about that experience some years later \u2014
p212
aVshe's a poet and psychotherapist named Maggie Robbins \u2014
p213
aVwhen I interviewed her, she said,
p214
aV"I was singing 'Where Have All The Flowers Gone,'
p215
aVover and over, to occupy my mind.
p216
aVI was singing to blot out the things my mind was saying,
p217
aVwhich were, 'You are nothing. You are nobody.
p218
aVYou don't even deserve to live.'
p219
aVAnd that was when I really started thinking
p220
aVabout killing myself."
p221
aa(lp222
VYou don't think in depression that you've put on a gray veil
p223
aVand are seeing the world through the haze of a bad mood.
p224
aVYou think that the veil has been taken away,
p225
aVthe veil of happiness,
p226
aVand that now you're seeing truly.
p227
aVIt's easier to help schizophrenics who perceive
p228
aVthat there's something foreign inside of them that needs to be exorcised,
p229
aVbut it's difficult with depressives,
p230
aVbecause we believe we are seeing the truth.
p231
aa(lp232
VBut the truth lies.
p233
aVI became obsessed with that sentence:
p234
aV"But the truth lies."
p235
aVAnd I discovered, as I talked to depressive people,
p236
aVthat they have many delusional perceptions.
p237
aVPeople will say, "No one loves me."
p238
aVAnd you say, "I love you,
p239
aVyour wife loves you, your mother loves you."
p240
aVYou can answer that one pretty readily, at least for most people.
p241
aVBut people who are depressed will also say,
p242
aV"No matter what we do, we're all just going to die in the end."
p243
aVOr they'll say, "There can be no true communion
p244
aVbetween two human beings.
p245
aVEach of us is trapped in his own body."
p246
aVTo which you have to say,
p247
aV"That's true,
p248
aVbut I think we should focus right now on what to have for breakfast."
